<subsection xml:id="subsec-determining-the-median-of-a-set-of-discrete-data-from-real-life-situations">
    <title>determining the median of a set of discrete data from real life situations</title>

    <p>
        The median of a data set is the middle value when the numbers are arranged in ascending (smallest to largest) or descending order.
    </p>
    <p>
        How to Find the Median:
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Arrange the data in order.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If the number of values is odd, the median is the middle number.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If the number of values is even, the median is the average of the two middle numbers.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{red} \textbf{Work in groups}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Taita secondary school football team coach recorded the heights (in cm) of <m>25</m> players on the team:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>175, 178, 180, 182, 185, 187, 190, 192, 195, 197, 200, 202,</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>205, 207, 210, 212, 215, 217, 220, 222, 225, 227, 230, 232, 235</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the median height of the players.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Explain what the median represents in this scenario
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \textbf{Learning Point}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        The item in the middle is the median when the items in a data set are sorted in ascending order.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A bakery recorded the number of loaves of bread sold each day for <m>30</m> days. The numbers are:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>50, 55, 60, 52, 58, 65, 70, 68, 72, 75, 80, 85, 90, 95, 100,</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>105, 110, 98, 92, 88, 78, 66, 62, 54, 59, 74, 82, 87, 97, 102</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the median number of loaves sold per day.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i.)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Arrange the data in ascending order
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>50, 52, 54, 55, 58, 59, 60, 62, 65, 66, 68, 70, 72, 74, 75, </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>78, 80, 82, 85, 87, 88, 90, 92, 95, 97, 98, 100, 102, 105, 110</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the middle values
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Since there are <m>30</m> values (even number), the median is the average of the <m>15th</m> and <m>16th</m> values.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>15th</m> value = <m> 75</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>16th</m> value = <m>78</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m> \textbf{Median} = \frac{75 + 78}{2} = 76.5</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The median number of loaves sold per day is <m>76.5</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
